    "body": "@zcbenz \n\n```\nC:\\Windows\\system32>[7296:0122/092731:INFO:CONSOLE(0)] [ { id: 2528732444,\n    bounds: { x: 0, y: 0, width: 1366, height: 768 },\n    workArea: { x: 0, y: 0, width: 1366, height: 738 },\n    size: { width: 1366, height: 768 },\n    workAreaSize: { width: 1366, height: 738 },\n    scaleFactor: 1,\n    rotation: 0,\n    touchSupport: 'unknown' },\n  { id: 2779098405,\n    bounds: { x: -1280, y: -256, width: 1280, height: 1024 },\n    workArea: { x: -1280, y: -256, width: 1280, height: 1024 },\n    size: { width: 1280, height: 1024 },\n    workAreaSize: { width: 1280, height: 1024 },\n    scaleFactor: 1,\n    rotation: 0,\n    touchSupport: 'unknown' },\n  { id: 2841568472,\n    bounds: { x: -2360, y: -688, width: 1080, height: 1920 },\n    workArea: { x: -2360, y: -688, width: 1080, height: 1920 },\n    size: { width: 1080, height: 1920 },\n    workAreaSize: { width: 1080, height: 1920 },\n    scaleFactor: 1,\n    rotation: 270,\n    touchSupport: 'unknown' } ]\n[11144:0122/095157:INFO:CONSOLE(0)] null\n```\n\n**See that the externalDisplay is null even though you can see three screens. This is because the X coords are actual minus... so the code only handles external displays on the right of the main display and not the left display.**\n\nHere's the code I ran:\n\n```\nvar app = require('app');\n\napp.on('ready', function() {\n\n    var screen = require('screen');\n    var displays = screen.getAllDisplays();\n\n    console.log( displays );\n\n    var externalDisplay = null;\n\n    for (var i in displays) {\n        if (displays[i].bounds.x > 0 || displays[i].bounds.y > 0) {\n            externalDisplay = displays[i];\n            break;\n        } else {\n\n        }\n    }\n\n    console.log( externalDisplay );\n\n});\n```\n"
